message: I don’t think I’ve been this excited to meet someone in quite some time. At this point, I think it’s fair to give you my number – please feel free to text me at 913 638 3229!

So many options! When do you have to dry dock the sailboat? If it's soon, we should definitely take advantage of the weather. Otherwise, I am always up for a small adventure! What do you have in mind?

Hey Michael! Yes, I’m free on Tuesday! And thank you! Only slightly overwhelmed with compliments, but even more impressed you did your research. (The paper craft is my favorite!) Took a look at your site. Between cats, potatoes, art and travel, we have a lot to talk about!

For next week, what would you like to do? I keep a sailboat at pier 40 off of W. Houston that I haven’t taken out in weeks (and I have to dry dock soon), but that might be more of a second or third date sort of thing. If you’d like to go on a small adventure, I’d love to do something unique with you. Or at the very least, I hope you’ll let me buy you a cup of coffee and hopefully dinner.

I may have creepily googled you and I love your website / personal brand. Your design aesthetic is nothing short of amazing. You are so incredibly creative. I especially love your papercrafts. If you’re not creeped out or overwhelmed with compliments, you can check out my site and read more about me at: https://mldangelo.com
Hey Sarah! Thank you. Yes! Are you free Tuesday or Wednesday?
I would love to hear more about you and your adventures. Are you by chance free next week?
Haha, are you kidding? Swoon category. The force is strong here. And so are your photos – was thinking the same about your Instagram!
It sounds like you've had some amazing opportunities while working in aerospace! I'm enthralled by your interest in it.
And now you either swoon or cringe depending on how terrible you thought that line was.  I love your Instagram. You’re a great photographer.

And great. As you know, Newton's law of universal gravitation relates the gravitational force between objects to their respective distance between them. It states f=G*m1*m2/r^2 where G is a constant, m1 and m2 are masses (you and me), and r is the distance between us. It means that by law, we are attracted to each other!

That’s amazing. I’m glad I inspired you. I used to work in aerospace and before that I helped run a nonprofit called SEDS (Students for the Exploration and Development of Space) which exposed me to a lot of high ranking aerospace people. The Sokol belonged to The Heinlein Prize Trust. They would take it around to conferences and very occasionally allow people to try it on. And the OrbitalOutfitters CEO that built the SpaceX prototype sat on SEDS’ board of advisors (along with Elon Musk, Bill Nye and others). Sadly, I’ve never had the opportunity to wear a space suit in a vacuum.
And yes, I am familiar with Newton's law of universal gravitation!
That is so cool! On what occasions did you get to try on these real space suits? You inspired me to read more about them today.
And that’s the cutest question I’ve ever been asked on tinder. Now for a space themed pick up line .... are you familiar with newton’s law of universal gravitation?

Hey Sarah! Space suits are real suits! In answer to your question:  a real suit, space suits are designed to be functional by engineers (and not fashion designers) and so most are really ugly. They’re also oddly constrictive. Fun fact, I’ve worn two real space suits in my life. A Russian made Sokol suit that went to the ISS via the Soyuz, and a prototype spacesuit manufactured for SpaceX and made by a company called orbitaloutfitters.
And I'm curious about what you're standing in!
Ok, so I'm not smooth with the lines, but you seem awesome and I'd love to get to know you more.
I'm trying to figure out if you'd look cuter in a space suit or a real suit... Thoughts?
